I have doen some cleaning in client.java and after I took a break and started the server, when a player logs in, it says "null". After some hard-core debugging (2 hours!), I believe I figured out the cause.

In IOClient.java, there is this code:
[code=java]
				else {
					final PlayerSave loadgame = loadGame(playerName, playerPass);
					if (loadgame != null) {
						System.out.println("1");
						if (!playerPass.equals(loadgame.playerPass))
							returnCode = 3;
						else {
[/code]
Now, take a look closely at:
[code=java]
					final PlayerSave loadgame = loadGame(playerName, playerPass);
					if (loadgame != null) {
[/code]
It is asking if it is not null. Now lets see what happens if it is null:
[code=java]
					} else
						c = new Client(socket, slot);
[/code]
So it is making the client null! Thus, since the Client.java is extended by Player.java, it carried the abstract void println, and the Client.java ends up spitting, "null".

Now, the prime cause is this:
[code=java]
final PlayerSave loadgame = loadGame(playerName, playerPass);
[/code]
More certainly, this:
[code=java]
loadGame(playerName, playerPass);
[/code]
I took a look at this method, and found this:
[code=java]
	public PlayerSave loadGame(final String playerName, final String playerPass) {
		PlayerSave tempPlayer;

		try {
			final ObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(
					new FileInputStream("./savedgames/" + playerName + ".dat"));
			tempPlayer = (PlayerSave) in.readObject();
			in.close();
		} catch (final Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
		return tempPlayer;
	}
[/code]
More thoroughly, I saw:
[code=java]
                try {
                        final ObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(
                                        new FileInputStream("./savedgames/" + playerName + ".dat"));
                        tempPlayer = (PlayerSave) in.readObject();
                        in.close();
                } catch (final Exception e) {
                        return null;
                }
[/code]
It is doing this:
[code=java]
                } catch (final Exception e) {
                        return null;
                }
[/code]
Not this:
[code=java]
                try {
                        final ObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(
                                        new FileInputStream("./savedgames/" + playerName + ".dat"));
                        tempPlayer = (PlayerSave) in.readObject();
                        in.close();
[/code]
What did it catch as an Exception to make it null?

